  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering at both the federal and state levels in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Currency and Foreign Transactions Reporting Act\n\n2. Key Federal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State Statutes:\n- Most states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- These typically mirror federal provisions and provide additional enforcement mechanisms\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- Various international treaties and agreements support anti-money laundering efforts\n\nThese statutes generally criminalize the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically through complex financial transactions, and establish reporting and compliance requirements for financial institutions.",
